issues.title: Disabled CSSproperties do not show up
issues.body: If you disable a property then select a different node that the disabled property was applied to,  nothing will appear because our API to get CSS applied to the node will not find it. Target behavior is showing the property as disabled.

issues.body: This issue tracks adding support to host the Chrome Dev Tools (that works with the adapter!) frontend remotely from the adapter.

issues.title: Breakpoints do not work in HTML files
issues.body: Breakpoints within a script tag in an HTML file are never hit.

Thanks Dick!

Try the following:
Under Internet options/advanced in Internet Explorer, ensure both "enable enhanced protective mode", and "enable 64 bit tabs for enhanced protective mode" are not checked. Then try using the 32 bit release.
using the 32bit release seems to fix it for me
No it should barely use the CPU at all. Are you able to identify steps to reproduce this? Or perhaps get a call stack?

All I did is start the program. There is no extra step.
I'm windows 7 x64
I had those checked off.  Using 32 bit resolved the issue. What's going on with the 64 bit ?

Did you try what @alexcope suggested? I had them unchecked so may be the x86 worked instantly without any errors. Software and OS versions are same as yours.

> Under Internet options/advanced in Internet Explorer, ensure both "enable enhanced protective mode", and "enable 64 bit tabs for enhanced protective mode" are not checked.

Hi **@praveenpuglia**, I'm your friendly neighborhood Microsoft Pull Request Bot (You can call me MSBOT). Thanks for your contribution! This seems like a small (but important) contribution, so no Contribution License Agreement is required at this point. Real humans will now evaluate your PR. TTYL, MSBOT;
Closing this issue since x86 worked but a bug for x64 remains. Wondering if I should create a new issue for it.
@bedney, can you clarify, do you mean, you'd like to be able to write an extension for IE that could work against IE using the protocol?
@praveenpuglia I've already tried that with no luck

It looks like a webpage specific issue rather than the adapter itself. That's the error you get when you use anything other than object as key in `WeakMap.prototype.set` in IE. Tried this to confirm 
    var wm = new WeakMap();
    wm.set("123",12);
Can you try a different web page and see if the issue persists?
Ok it works for other pages, thanks @praveenpuglia

On windows 7 x64 I can confirm High CPU Usage. Mine was almost always about 25% or more. Even when not debugging a page.

After couple of observations I saw that it is fixed at 25% no matter what. Strange.
Nice! Please mark it as closed. I can't do that yet.

@danmosemsft - Thanks for the quick reply.

Yes. On Chrome, we leverage this capability by loading a Chrome extension into Chrome and speak the debugging protocol directly to a Chrome task with no server involved. The wireline protocol is the same, but you attach directly to the target. The API is detailed on that page I linked to above.
I do think we should keep it open since it will be fixed on x64 also.

We don't have plans to extend this to IE extensions yet or enabling extensions of F12. 

That being said we are keen for the F12 tools to have a HTML/JS extension model that is highly interoperable with Chrome. No plans yet though and we're going to wait for the Project Spartan extensibility model plans before plans for F12 can be made.

@andysterland - Thanks for the reply! I can't tell you how cool it is to see Microsoft people on GitHub, collaborating with their developer community! :-)

I understand the desire to wait and see how Spartan might change the extensibility model. If you guys could keep a capability like this in mind when that shakes out, that'd be great. Thanks!
